            </form>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
                        
                        <p>That&rsquo;s the problem with sportswriting, if you do it for long enough: The spectacle you&rsquo;re going to see&mdash;and the Final Four really is a spectacle, and you couldn&rsquo;t have asked for better seats than the ones I was watching from&mdash;loses some of its luster, because you have to think about what comes after, whether it&rsquo;s a story, a blog post or an entire newspaper. You can&rsquo;t focus on the amazing skill you&rsquo;re seeing just feet in front of you. Instead, you have to focus on the words players and coaches mumble in the press room, where neither party really wants to be, or in the locker room, a place where short, white, Jewish journalists like myself don&rsquo;t belong.</p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p>And it&rsquo;s a shame, because as Alex Fanaroff wrote in his pseudo-farewell column last week, athletics let you see life in a special way. Sports have always allowed me to feel like part of the team&mdash;to pretend I could sink that jump shot, make that throw or chip that soccer ball into the top-right corner of the goal&mdash;and being at a school with such a great athletic program has accentuated that feeling. I gleefully chanted &ldquo;BCS! BCS!&rdquo; after Duke, in Coach Cutcliffe&rsquo;s first game, beat James Madison at Wally Wade. I jumped up and down on the Koskinen Stadium bleachers during a men&rsquo;s soccer game against Carolina my freshman year, before basketball season even started, as Duke held onto a one-goal lead with 10 men. I waited out two injury timeouts, a rain delay and a change of venue to watch Reid Carleton&rsquo;s incredible comeback against UNC on the tennis court. I&rsquo;ve yelled unconscionable things at visiting basketball players. And as anyone who knows me well would tell you, I&rsquo;ve proudly worn green and orange twice into Wallace Wade Stadium and rooted for my team&mdash;Miami, not Duke&mdash;and I can&rsquo;t wait to do it again. That&rsquo;s what sports are about: a feeling of real connection with something bigger than you. There&rsquo;s nothing contrived about it, at least not at the college level.</p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p>Journalism&mdash;not sports journalism, but the process of reporting a meaningful story with a measurable impact&mdash;has allowed me to feel something similar. Becoming a journalist has been the defining aspect of my college experience, and it has given me the chance to meet some of the most fascinating and insightful people on this campus, particularly the dearly departed Susan Tifft. For me, journalism was the door that had been cracked open since the moment I moved into Bell Tower four years ago, and now, four years later, that door is all the way open. I know this University more deeply than I never thought I would, and I&rsquo;m not just talking about the Department of Athletics.</p>
<p></p>

                                                    <div class="related my-4 py-4 d-print-none">
                                <h3 class="kicker mb-4">Read more</h3>

                                                                                                                
            
        
