                    </article>

                                                                                                </div>
                        

                        <p></p>
<p>I&rsquo;ve also been challenged intellectually as a member of The Chronicle as much as or more than I ever was in a Duke classroom, and that&rsquo;s why I was so willing to trudge up the three flights of stairs to 301 Flowers hundreds, maybe thousands of times since August. I did more than my fair share of grunt work, yet much of the time, being a part of the journalistic process was a thrill, and the freedom I had to mold the sports section as I saw fit meant a lot to me.</p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p>But at this point, with literally days remaining in what I consider my childhood, I&rsquo;m done. I can&rsquo;t do it anymore. I&rsquo;ve given The Chronicle countless precious hours of my senior year&mdash;too many, if you ask my friends, girlfriend or parents&mdash;and with this column, I signal the end of my brief, shooting-star-like career as a sports journalist. I only wish I had been able to retire at my absolute apex, which truly was un-four-gettable.</p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p>The chance I had to write that national championship story&mdash;an opportunity only three other people in the 105-year history of The Chronicle have had&mdash;is one I will always be grateful for. And while I&rsquo;ve fallen out of love with sportswriting, I won&rsquo;t ever fall out of love with sports. The World Cup, football season and Duke Basketball&rsquo;s national championship defense are right around the corner, and I&rsquo;ll be watching every step of the way.</p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
                                    </div>

